# Repository-Specific SQL & Cypher Query Generator (Tutorial-First, Local, Production-Grade)

This project builds a specialized, schema-aware Text-to-SQL and Text-to-Cypher assistant.

It is written as a practical mini-book and runnable engineering system:
- tutorial notebooks,
- reusable Python modules,
- CLI pipelines,
- QLoRA fine-tuning,
- baseline-vs-fine-tuned evaluation,
- Neo4j execution demo.

All stages run locally with `uv` and Python `3.12.10`.

## 1. Problem Statement

Natural-language query generation is deceptively hard.

### Why Text-to-SQL is hard
- Schema grounding: mapping words to real tables/columns.
- Join correctness: wrong join paths produce wrong business outcomes.
- Aggregation/nesting: high syntactic and semantic fragility.
- Ambiguity: user questions omit constraints.
- Hallucination: models invent schema fields.

### Why Text-to-Cypher is harder
- Graph patterns require relationship-centric reasoning.
- Directionality matters (`->` vs `<-`).
- Multi-hop traversal planning is nontrivial.
- SQL mental models do not transfer directly to graph patterns.

This project explicitly addresses these issues with:
- schema-aware prompts,
- SQL parsing and normalization,
- SQL-to-Cypher hybrid label generation,
- fine-tuning,
- validation and error analysis,
- execution benchmarking.

## 2. Dataset Strategy

### Primary training data (required)
- `Clinton/Text-to-sql-v1` (Hugging Face)

Verified structure:
- columns: `instruction`, `input`, `response`, `source`, `text`
- rows: 262,208
- many source domains (`wikisql`, `sql_create_context`, `spider`, etc.)

Observed complexity includes joins, grouping, order clauses, and nested queries.

### Execution benchmark subset
- Official Spider SQLite DB bundle (downloaded for evaluation only)

Why add Spider for execution metrics:
- primary dataset is SQL text-focused and not uniformly DB-backed for execution benchmarking.
- Spider provides real DB files for true execution equivalence checks.

## 3. Model Choices and Tradeoffs

### Fine-tuned target: Granite 4.1 3B family
Selected because:
- best local fit under 6 GB VRAM constraint,
- practical QLoRA memory profile,
- strong schema instruction behavior for its size.

Tradeoffs:
- lower absolute capacity than larger models,
- but substantially better feasibility for reproducible local tuning.

### Baseline and judge comparator: Qwen 3.5 4B
Selected because:
- strong non-fine-tuned baseline quality,
- useful independent judge model for LLM-as-a-judge.

Tradeoffs:
- heavier runtime and tighter VRAM margin for fine-tuning.

### Embedding model: qwen3-embedding:4b
Selected because:
- available locally,
- improved schema/context retrieval quality vs very small embedders.

Tradeoff:
- higher embedding compute/storage than tiny models.

### Not selected for core task: glm-ocr
Reason:
- OCR is not core to text-to-query generation.
- kept optional for future document-ingestion extensions.

## 3.1 Fine-Tuning Framework Choices (PEFT, TRL, Unsloth)

### PEFT (used)
- Definition: Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning using adapters (LoRA) on a frozen base model.
- Why used: enables local adapter training for 3B-scale models under tight VRAM.
- Where used: all training backends (`hf`, `trl`, and conditional `unsloth`).
- What changed: training now saves portable adapter artifacts with explicit backend metadata.

### TRL (used when available)
- Definition: Training library with `SFTTrainer` and `SFTConfig` for supervised instruction tuning.
- Why used: cleaner instruction-tuning semantics and direct support for prompt-completion style data.
- Where used: primary backend when installed (`--backend trl` or `auto`).
- What changed: supervised fine-tuning path now supports TRL-native configuration and logging.

### Unsloth (conditionally used)
- Definition: accelerated training framework integrated with TRL.
- Why used: potential speed and VRAM gains only when model/runtime compatibility is verified.
- Where used: optional backend (`--backend unsloth`) behind strict compatibility checks.
- What changed: if compatibility fails (for example, unsupported base model family), pipeline falls back to TRL/HF and records the reason in training metadata.

